## 2. Plastic Production & the Oil Pivot (Macro Layer)

### 2.1 The Plastic Boom
- Market: ~$524.48B in 2024 → ~$754.23B by 2032 (p.7).
- Production: 2 Mt (1950) → 460 Mt (2019) → 1,231 Mt (2060 projection); waste 353 Mt (2019) → 1,014 Mt (2060) (p.7).
- Supply-driven lock-in: 333 new/expanded projects since 2010; $200B invested (p.7–8).
- Since Nov 2022: seven majors added 1.4 Mt new capacity; Shell PA adds 1.6 Mt/yr polyethylene; Exxon cracker for Asia export (p.8).

### 2.2 The Recycling Myth
- Recycling rate: ~9% globally; 5–6% U.S. (p.13). Disposal: ~49–50% landfill, ~19% incinerated, ~22% mismanaged leakage (p.13).
- Mechanical limits: downcycling after 1–2 cycles; contamination and polymer incompatibility block circularity (p.13–14).
- “Advanced” (chemical) recycling: energy-intensive, high pollution, outputs mostly low-grade fuel (p.14).
- PR deception: internal docs show industry knew recycling was infeasible since the 1970s; 1980s chasing-arrows campaign shifted blame to consumers; California 2024 suit vs ExxonMobil alleges 50-year deception (p.14, p.286).
- Exxon “advanced recycling” uses <1% plastic waste as feed for new plastic (p.286).
- Line: “Recycling was never designed to solve plastic – it was designed to protect plastic.”

### 2.3 Why This Matters for the Rest of the Book
- Pattern primer: an industrial lie normalized at scale.
- Same actors, same playbook: subsidies, PR, externalized costs — a template for corruption, AI safety theater, and control themes later.

